  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?**:\r\n/kind bug\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\n\r\nFor extremely high volumes of requests (e.g. many pod create requests, each doing many PSP authorization calls, detailed [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1IIcHHE_No1KMAybW5krIphdN325eGa2sxF2eqg2YAPI/edit#)), the log line in the RBAC authorizer becomes a bottleneck:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/cbdd18eee97369197dc3db0d3c85bf261e529903/plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go#L116\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nI expect RBAC to be able to handle high volumes of simultaneous authorizations. A couple options include:\r\n\r\n- Raise the verbosity level on that log, basically disabling it when high performance is a concern (suggested by @liggitt , now that we have better audit logging)\r\n- Throttling the log write rate, skipping writes when the rate is too high\r\n- Buffering the log (maybe in combination with the throttle)\r\n\r\nEither way, the PodSecurityPolicy case is not working as intended, I don't think writing thousands of denies for PodSecurityPolicies to the log is useful (we could also just skip logging on the `use` verb).\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\nSee [PodSecurityPolicy Scale Testing](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1IIcHHE_No1KMAybW5krIphdN325eGa2sxF2eqg2YAPI/edit#heading=h.1ns3f93w7sor) (although it will be somewhat fixed by https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/55643)\r\n\r\n/cc @kubernetes/sig-scalability-bugs @kubernetes/sig-auth-bugs ",
